  "alm_dt_tilt": "Earth\u2019s Tilt",
  "alm_dt_tilt_desc": "This tilt is why seasons exist. It\u2019s currently {trend}, meaning: {impact}. Cycles between 22.1\u00b0 and 24.5\u00b0 over 41,000 years (Milankovi\u0107 cycle). Currently {pct}% through the cycle.",
  "alm_dt_polaris": "Polaris Accuracy",
  "alm_dt_polaris_desc": "Earth wobbles like a spinning top. Polaris happens to be near the axis right now, but it\u2019s drifting. Closest alignment ~2100 (0.45\u00b0), then it drifts away. In ~{years} years, Vega will be the \u201cNorth Star.\u201d Full wobble cycle: 25,772 years.",
  "alm_dt_daylen": "Today Is Longer Than Yesterday",
  "alm_dt_daylen_desc": "The Moon\u2019s gravity creates tides that act like brakes on Earth\u2019s spin. Each century, days grow 1.8ms longer. Since the year 2000, days have stretched {ms}ms. Doesn\u2019t sound like much \u2014 but 600 million years ago, a day was only 21 hours. The Moon drifts 3.8 cm farther each year, slowly releasing its grip.",
  "alm_dt_orbit": "Orbit Shape",
  "alm_dt_orbit_desc": "How elliptical Earth\u2019s orbit is (0 = perfect circle, 1 = extremely stretched). Currently near-circular and {trend}. This affects how much solar energy Earth receives over a year. Combined with tilt and precession, these three cycles drive ice ages (Milankovi\u0107 theory).",
  "alm_dt_julian": "Julian Date",
  "alm_dt_julian_desc": "A continuous count of days since January 1, 4713 BC. Used by astronomers because it never resets, skips, or changes with calendar reforms. Every event in human history has exactly one Julian Date. Immune to leap seconds, timezone changes, and political calendars.",
  "alm_dt_galactic": "Galactic Year",
  "alm_dt_galactic_desc": "The Sun orbits the Milky Way\u2019s center every ~225 million years at 828,000 km/h. In {age} billion years, we\u2019ve completed roughly {orbits} orbits. Last time we were here, dinosaurs ruled the Earth.",
